260
00:11:47.730 --> 00:11:49.530
<v ->I always tell people there's a lot of tumble down</v>

261
00:11:49.530 --> 00:11:51.630
all of a sudden when you get that diagnosis,

262
00:11:51.630 --> 00:11:53.790
you know, in terms of vaccines, medications,

263
00:11:53.790 --> 00:11:54.840
et cetera, et cetera.

264
00:11:55.710 --> 00:12:00.210
<v ->And then FARXIGA can be used in diabetes down to GFR</v>

265
00:12:00.210 --> 00:12:01.530
according to UpToDate.

266
00:12:01.530 --> 00:12:04.470
Yeah, so these numbers are all changing

267
00:12:04.470 --> 00:12:07.560
and they're pushing the GFRs down lower and lower.

268
00:12:07.560 --> 00:12:10.230
And you'll notice, I mean, I had 60, 45,

269
00:12:10.230 --> 00:12:11.970
and then down at the bottom it's like, you know,

270
00:12:11.970 --> 00:12:13.650
use them down to 30.

271
00:12:13.650 --> 00:12:16.440
So there are gonna be differences between what it says to

272
00:12:16.440 --> 00:12:19.053
on the package insert and what we're using them to.

273
00:12:20.040 --> 00:12:22.530
So I realize that's confusing,

274
00:12:22.530 --> 00:12:26.910
but we're trying to use them down to a GFR of 30.

275
00:12:26.910 --> 00:12:30.180
And someone asked about the point about contraceptives.

276
00:12:30.180 --> 00:12:34.770
If you have a teenager on an ACE or an ARB,

277
00:12:34.770 --> 00:12:37.980
then you have to make sure they're on a contraceptive

278
00:12:37.980 --> 00:12:40.290
so they don't get pregnant on the ACE and ARB.

279
00:12:40.290 --> 00:12:43.618
And the recommended would be an IUD or an Nexplanon,

280
00:12:43.618 --> 00:12:46.290
not just an oral contraceptive.

281
00:12:46.290 --> 00:12:49.290
<v ->I had a patient leave her obstetrician not recently,</v>

282
00:12:49.290 --> 00:12:53.550
and the ACE was continued as she was trying to get pregnant.

283
00:12:53.550 --> 00:12:55.440
They had taken her for birth control and she saw me

284
00:12:55.440 --> 00:12:57.840
and I'm like, "Your blood pressure's not controlled

285
00:12:57.840 --> 00:12:59.880
and you should not be on that medication any longer."

286
00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:01.530
She said "What?"

287
00:13:01.530 --> 00:13:02.640
Okay.

288
00:13:02.640 --> 00:13:04.713
<v ->And then hep B,</v>

289
00:13:05.790 --> 00:13:07.980
why do we give the vaccine in adults?

290
00:13:07.980 --> 00:13:10.500
Because it's really because diet,

291
00:13:10.500 --> 00:13:12.540
people with diabetes are going to deal

292
00:13:12.540 --> 00:13:14.280
with a lot of needles,

293
00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:18.810
either insulin or now with the GLP ones or finger sticks

294
00:13:18.810 --> 00:13:22.379
or, you know, there's just too much of that

295
00:13:22.379 --> 00:13:25.650
and it's so easy to just vaccinate for hepatitis B.

296
00:13:25.650 --> 00:13:27.960
We already know how good vaccines are, right?

297
00:13:27.960 --> 00:13:29.430
<v ->Yes.</v>
<v ->So we should give</v>

298
00:13:29.430 --> 00:13:30.263
the vaccine.

299
00:13:30.263 --> 00:13:33.360
<v ->Well, and keep in mind, in 2023,</v>

300
00:13:33.360 --> 00:13:35.880
ASIP finally said, "You know what, we've got so many groups,

301
00:13:35.880 --> 00:13:38.490
everybody can get vaccinated with hepatitis B now."

302
00:13:38.490 --> 00:13:42.510
You know, we caught everybody up after we did the kids

303
00:13:42.510 --> 00:13:43.920
and everybody didn't get caught up.

304
00:13:43.920 --> 00:13:48.900
So there's this window of about 35 or 40 till about 60

305
00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:50.340
that people have not been immunized.

306
00:13:50.340 --> 00:13:53.250
Now, anybody can get the hep B vaccine

307
00:13:53.250 --> 00:13:56.190
per the ASIP recommendations if you haven't had one, okay?

308
00:13:56.190 --> 00:13:59.250
You never get more than two series.

309
00:13:59.250 --> 00:14:02.190
So if you don't respond to the first series,

310
00:14:02.190 --> 00:14:03.660
you can get a second series,

311
00:14:03.660 --> 00:14:05.940
but you never get more than two,

312
00:14:05.940 --> 00:14:10.050
and there is no recommendation to routinely evaluate

313
00:14:10.050 --> 00:14:13.463
for response to the hepatitis B series, okay?

314
00:14:14.856 --> 00:14:17.441
<v ->And the last thing I'm just gonna say, no one,</v>

315
00:14:17.441 --> 00:14:21.671
we don't have a USPSTF recommendation or anything for B12,

316
00:14:21.671 --> 00:14:24.840
checking B12 in people who are metformin.

317
00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:27.000
And so should we do it every year?

318
00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.880
I don't know, some of the newer studies are suggesting that,

319
00:14:29.880 --> 00:14:31.320
but this is the problem.

320
00:14:31.320 --> 00:14:33.780
There are thousands of diabetics out there

321
00:14:33.780 --> 00:14:36.630
who are on metformin who've never had a B12 checked.

322
00:14:36.630 --> 00:14:40.140
And so I don't care if their CBC looks okay,

323
00:14:40.140 --> 00:14:42.120
people who have not had a B12 check

324
00:14:42.120 --> 00:14:45.690
who are on metformin need that to happen.

325
00:14:45.690 --> 00:14:46.593
<v ->Dr. Garry.</v>

326
00:14:51.750 --> 00:14:55.830
<v ->Okay, so several questions here.</v>

327
00:14:55.830 --> 00:15:00.150
One on individuals who are ordering x-rays.

328
00:15:00.150 --> 00:15:02.010
And then I have to wait

329
00:15:02.010 --> 00:15:06.420
and I've got to wait maybe days to get a radiology,

330
00:15:06.420 --> 00:15:08.700
a radiologist's interpretation of the x-ray.

331
00:15:08.700 --> 00:15:10.170
What should I do with it?

332
00:15:10.170 --> 00:15:12.930
Well, I think, A, I'm ordering the x-ray,

333
00:15:12.930 --> 00:15:14.850
it's imperative that I look at the x-ray.

334
00:15:14.850 --> 00:15:16.860
So you have to have access to the x-ray.

335
00:15:16.860 --> 00:15:19.650
You're gonna have to make a judgment

336
00:15:19.650 --> 00:15:23.970
without having the radiologist's interpretation.

337
00:15:23.970 --> 00:15:27.150
It's recognized, so this question's leading

338
00:15:27.150 --> 00:15:28.950
to medical legal risk.

339
00:15:28.950 --> 00:15:33.870
It's recognized that, that you're not a radiologist.

340
00:15:33.870 --> 00:15:36.660
In the practice I came from at Minnesota,

341
00:15:36.660 --> 00:15:38.880
we read our own images.

342
00:15:38.880 --> 00:15:41.730
We could request an overread by radiology,

343
00:15:41.730 --> 00:15:43.380
but we read our own images

344
00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:47.073
and then subsequently, we billed for that portion of it.

345
00:15:48.330 --> 00:15:52.140
But, so we can do that as a family medicine physician

346
00:15:52.140 --> 00:15:54.120
or primary care physicians,

347
00:15:54.120 --> 00:15:57.750
but it's imperative if you're ordering the imaging study

348
00:15:57.750 --> 00:15:59.640
that you're looking at it

349
00:15:59.640 --> 00:16:01.710
and you're making an interpretation.

350
00:16:01.710 --> 00:16:05.100
If I overtreat, okay, I overtreat, I'm not a radiologist,

351
00:16:05.100 --> 00:16:07.260
but you know, I don't,

352
00:16:07.260 --> 00:16:09.780
I can't order it and say, "Well, you know,

353
00:16:09.780 --> 00:16:12.420
there's this big mass there and I just,

354
00:16:12.420 --> 00:16:13.470
I didn't know what it was,

355
00:16:13.470 --> 00:16:16.560
so I didn't do anything about it for three or four days

356
00:16:16.560 --> 00:16:17.393
until the radiologist said,

357
00:16:17.393 --> 00:16:20.617
'There's a big mass there,'" right?

358
00:16:20.617 --> 00:16:22.170
"You got to do this."

359
00:16:22.170 --> 00:16:25.800
So you have to do that.

360
00:16:25.800 --> 00:16:28.623
That's, I guess all I can say about that.

361
00:16:31.710 --> 00:16:36.710
DXA is used for screening osteoporosis to avoid fractures,

362
00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:38.850
but doesn't a fragility fracture

363
00:16:38.850 --> 00:16:41.340
by definition confirm osteoporosis?

364
00:16:41.340 --> 00:16:43.890
Yes, it does from a clinical standpoint,

365
00:16:43.890 --> 00:16:48.717
but now I'm gonna implement treatment, I wanna get the DXA.

366
00:16:48.717 --> 00:16:51.210
The DXA is a relatively inexpensive test

367
00:16:51.210 --> 00:16:53.520
for everything that we do.

368
00:16:53.520 --> 00:16:56.430
I don't know, I mean, my best insurance pays

369
00:16:56.430 --> 00:16:59.850
maybe 300 bucks for a DXA with the interpretation.

370
00:16:59.850 --> 00:17:01.920
Most of them pay less than that.

371
00:17:01.920 --> 00:17:04.980
So it's a quick, it's an easy test.

372
00:17:04.980 --> 00:17:09.980
And I have quantitative data to compare to my follow-up

373
00:17:11.730 --> 00:17:14.760
two years later, sometimes one year later,

374
00:17:14.760 --> 00:17:16.710
depending on the severity of it.

375
00:17:16.710 --> 00:17:19.320
And I can see exactly what's happening.

376
00:17:19.320 --> 00:17:21.150
Am I reforming bone?

377
00:17:21.150 --> 00:17:23.790
Is my bone density actually going up?

378
00:17:23.790 --> 00:17:28.790
And the key to this is once you get a DXA on a patient,

379
00:17:29.880 --> 00:17:31.710
you want the second DXA

380
00:17:31.710 --> 00:17:35.520
or subsequent DXA should be on the same machine.

381
00:17:35.520 --> 00:17:37.500
So ask them where they had it

382
00:17:37.500 --> 00:17:39.150
and then work with your insurer.

383
00:17:39.150 --> 00:17:41.010
And your insurer will pay anybody

384
00:17:41.010 --> 00:17:43.200
to get the DXA on the same machine,

385
00:17:43.200 --> 00:17:45.630
even if they switch insurances.

386
00:17:45.630 --> 00:17:46.833
<v ->Dr. Blackwelder.</v>

387
00:17:47.670 --> 00:17:49.230
<v ->Yeah, we'll talk more about osteoporosis</v>

388
00:17:49.230 --> 00:17:50.160
in my next lecture.

389
00:17:50.160 --> 00:17:53.790
So some of my questions Dr. Garry gave you the answer to.

390
00:17:53.790 --> 00:17:55.540
We'll see how closely you listened.

391
00:17:56.880 --> 00:17:58.980
There, the most popular question was,

392
00:17:58.980 --> 00:18:01.770
what degree of hearing loss do you recommend hearing aids

393
00:18:01.770 --> 00:18:03.720
to reduce the risk of dementia?

394
00:18:03.720 --> 00:18:07.230
We used to have a lecture on dementia in the board review,

395
00:18:07.230 --> 00:18:08.583
but it was so depressing.

396
00:18:12.810 --> 00:18:14.640
I mean, it was depressing.

397
00:18:14.640 --> 00:18:15.600
Well-
<v ->It didn't,</v>

398
00:18:15.600 --> 00:18:17.880
any lecture on dementia is depressing.

399
00:18:17.880 --> 00:18:19.680
<v ->And it hasn't gotten any better.</v>

400
00:18:19.680 --> 00:18:20.513
<v ->No.</v>

401
00:18:20.513 --> 00:18:21.360
<v ->It would've gotten more,</v>

402
00:18:21.360 --> 00:18:22.410
the things I would've had to say

403
00:18:22.410 --> 00:18:25.020
this time would've been even more depressing.

404
00:18:25.020 --> 00:18:27.660
Although, I'm very aggressive with this.

405
00:18:27.660 --> 00:18:28.680
So if I have a patient

406
00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:30.930
and there's any element of hearing loss,

407
00:18:30.930 --> 00:18:33.720
I mean, we're quick to get hearing testing

408
00:18:33.720 --> 00:18:36.240
and really advocating for them to get

409
00:18:36.240 --> 00:18:38.190
some kind of hearing aids to help them.

410
00:18:39.960 --> 00:18:40.980
I didn't include this in my,

411
00:18:40.980 --> 00:18:43.770
I have a slide about dementia prevention in my last lecture,

412
00:18:43.770 --> 00:18:46.050
but this has come to my attention

413
00:18:46.050 --> 00:18:48.060
since I submitted my slides.

414
00:18:48.060 --> 00:18:49.800
The Lancet every few years does

415
00:18:49.800 --> 00:18:51.970
a dementia prevention summary

416
00:18:52.860 --> 00:18:55.830
and they just had one they published in 2022

417
00:18:55.830 --> 00:18:58.920
and they go through, it was like 12 things now

418
00:18:58.920 --> 00:19:00.810
that we're having emerging evidence

419
00:19:00.810 --> 00:19:02.700
to reduce the risk of dementia.

420
00:19:02.700 --> 00:19:06.690
If we really focused on those things like hearing loss,

421
00:19:06.690 --> 00:19:10.350
don't smoke, exercise, diet,

422
00:19:10.350 --> 00:19:13.983
we could prevent 40% of dementias worldwide.

423
00:19:15.180 --> 00:19:18.540
Now imagine if we had a medicine all of a sudden

424
00:19:18.540 --> 00:19:20.793
that prevented 40% of dementias.

425
00:19:21.690 --> 00:19:24.780
Think about the money behind that, right?

426
00:19:24.780 --> 00:19:27.840
So I'm becoming more and more aggressive with this,

427
00:19:27.840 --> 00:19:30.690
with the hearing aids and those type of things.

428
00:19:30.690 --> 00:19:34.620
I also think this ties in a lot out of COVID.

429
00:19:34.620 --> 00:19:37.800
We've learned the risk of social isolation

430
00:19:37.800 --> 00:19:39.480
and cognitive impairment.

431
00:19:39.480 --> 00:19:43.680
So if somebody can't hear, they're more likely to seclude

432
00:19:43.680 --> 00:19:45.990
and not interact with their friends.

433
00:19:45.990 --> 00:19:47.913
So all of this just spirals.

434
00:19:49.768 --> 00:19:51.840
So good question, that was a popular one.

435
00:19:51.840 --> 00:19:56.040
The other was asking for some clarification

436
00:19:56.040 --> 00:20:00.303
about Medicare plans, (chuckles)

437
00:20:01.440 --> 00:20:02.440
which is complicated

438
00:20:04.020 --> 00:20:08.370
as the healthcare marketplace has grown,

439
00:20:08.370 --> 00:20:11.100
there are now independent insurance brokers

440
00:20:11.100 --> 00:20:13.590
to help guide patients through this.

441
00:20:13.590 --> 00:20:15.330
If you can find somebody trustworthy,

442
00:20:15.330 --> 00:20:18.540
they're a good resource potentially

443
00:20:18.540 --> 00:20:20.100
'cause what happens is people don't know

444
00:20:20.100 --> 00:20:21.900
what they're getting.

445
00:20:21.900 --> 00:20:24.547
So then all of a sudden, a few years later they're like,

446
00:20:24.547 --> 00:20:27.277
"Oh, I need rehab because I didn't have a DXA

447
00:20:27.277 --> 00:20:29.460
and now I have a hip fracture."

448
00:20:29.460 --> 00:20:32.850
And their insurance is a pain paying for their rehab.

449
00:20:32.850 --> 00:20:34.620
So again, if you can encourage your person

450
00:20:34.620 --> 00:20:36.990
to get the best plan and all the bells and whistles

451
00:20:36.990 --> 00:20:38.100
as early as possible,

452
00:20:38.100 --> 00:20:40.620
that's gonna benefit them down the road.

453
00:20:40.620 --> 00:20:44.520
Another thing too, for these Medicare Advantage plans,

454
00:20:44.520 --> 00:20:47.370
a lot of them require more pre-auths,

455
00:20:47.370 --> 00:20:50.013
they also are geographic dependent.

456
00:20:50.940 --> 00:20:53.520
So potentially, their plan is administered in,

457
00:20:53.520 --> 00:20:54.990
let's say, South Carolina,

458
00:20:54.990 --> 00:20:58.620
and they go visit their daughter in Ohio

459
00:20:58.620 --> 00:21:00.240
for months out of the year.

460
00:21:00.240 --> 00:21:02.340
They might not be able to get care

461
00:21:02.340 --> 00:21:04.680
as opposed to just traditional Medicare A and B.

462
00:21:04.680 --> 00:21:06.030
They can get care anywhere.

463
00:21:07.200 --> 00:21:10.500
So it's complicated and in fairness,

464
00:21:10.500 --> 00:21:12.360
we don't learn enough about this.

465
00:21:12.360 --> 00:21:13.500
What I reviewed in my lecture,

466
00:21:13.500 --> 00:21:15.270
kind of those basic nuts and bolts,

467
00:21:15.270 --> 00:21:18.420
those would be the things that would be on your board exam.

468
00:21:18.420 --> 00:21:20.370
<v ->Dr. Garry, you have another one?</v>

469
00:21:20.370 --> 00:21:21.213
<v ->Sure.</v>

470
00:21:24.600 --> 00:21:26.340
Vertebral compression fractures,

471
00:21:26.340 --> 00:21:28.165
do you use a TLSO,

472
00:21:28.165 --> 00:21:31.950
a thoraco-lumbo-sacral orthoses or a back brace?

473
00:21:31.950 --> 00:21:34.980
You can for pain.

474
00:21:34.980 --> 00:21:37.860
And usually, we make that determination very quickly.

475
00:21:37.860 --> 00:21:40.110
Patient's gonna have to be admitted to the hospital

476
00:21:40.110 --> 00:21:44.700
for the most part and they're gonna have to have enough pain

477
00:21:44.700 --> 00:21:47.400
that I'm trying to get them up and get them moving.

478
00:21:47.400 --> 00:21:49.740
So I wanna get them fitted with this brace

479
00:21:49.740 --> 00:21:51.900
so that they can get up and get moving.

480
00:21:51.900 --> 00:21:54.180
You're usually not using it very long,

481
00:21:54.180 --> 00:21:57.420
so it's a really expensive intervention,

482
00:21:57.420 --> 00:22:02.040
but if it helps me get them moving, then it's beneficial.

483
00:22:02.040 --> 00:22:04.470
And then, of course,

484
00:22:04.470 --> 00:22:07.290
you know, the questions about bisphosphonates,

485
00:22:07.290 --> 00:22:09.060
can I use them?

486
00:22:09.060 --> 00:22:12.960
Can I go from PO to IV and tack on another five years?

487
00:22:12.960 --> 00:22:16.770
No, the answer is it's IV or PO, it's five,

488
00:22:16.770 --> 00:22:19.140
you add it all up, it's five years.

489
00:22:19.140 --> 00:22:21.810
And then what about vertebral plasty?

490
00:22:21.810 --> 00:22:24.120
And no one asked about kyphoplasty.

491
00:22:24.120 --> 00:22:29.120
But again, are you gonna talk about vertebral plasty?

492
00:22:29.130 --> 00:22:30.953
<v ->I'm not, not that-</v>
<v ->Okay.</v>

493
00:22:32.310 --> 00:22:34.890
I specifically don't talk about it.

494
00:22:34.890 --> 00:22:36.543
I know it's still being done.

495
00:22:37.500 --> 00:22:40.050
There's not any good evidence that it's beneficial

496
00:22:40.050 --> 00:22:43.440
or it changes any outcomes and it's expensive.

497
00:22:43.440 --> 00:22:46.380
And so I don't advise it,

498
00:22:46.380 --> 00:22:51.380
but it's still being done so.

499
00:22:51.450 --> 00:22:53.700
<v ->Dr. Vail, you have one last one?</v>

500
00:22:53.700 --> 00:22:56.880
<v ->Well, someone asked about the oral semaglutide.</v>

501
00:22:56.880 --> 00:22:58.590
So there is an oral form,

502
00:22:58.590 --> 00:23:02.760
it's marked as RYBELSUS for diabetes

503
00:23:02.760 --> 00:23:04.600
and it just doesn't work as well

504
00:23:06.302 --> 00:23:08.430
as the injectable form, particularly for weight loss.

505
00:23:08.430 --> 00:23:10.883
So unfortunately, it's not,

506
00:23:10.883 --> 00:23:13.380
I don't think it's gonna get licensed for weight loss

507
00:23:13.380 --> 00:23:14.970
'cause it just doesn't work that well.

508
00:23:14.970 --> 00:23:16.290
So too bad.

509
00:23:16.290 --> 00:23:17.700
<v ->And Dr. Blackwelder, one last thing?</v>

510
00:23:17.700 --> 00:23:19.200
You're good, okay.

511
00:23:19.200 --> 00:23:20.730
Please join me in thanking our speakers.

512
00:23:20.730 --> 00:23:22.245
They're all gonna be back this afternoon.

513
00:23:22.245 --> 00:23:24.510
(audience applauding)

