with autologous plasma injections in osteoarthritis,

772
00:35:22.500 --> 00:35:27.500
but just as you have with like hyaluronic acid or steroids,

773
00:35:29.122 --> 00:35:33.990
the lasting treatment or effects is very small.

774
00:35:33.990 --> 00:35:36.360
So you're gonna see more, you're gonna see greater benefit

775
00:35:36.360 --> 00:35:40.560
with autologous plasma injections for tendinopathies

776
00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:43.410
and less effect with an osteoarthritis.

777
00:35:43.410 --> 00:35:46.320
If you have chronic severe osteoarthritis,

778
00:35:46.320 --> 00:35:47.490
the only thing that's gonna cure

779
00:35:47.490 --> 00:35:49.290
that is a joint replacement.

780
00:35:49.290 --> 00:35:53.253
Everything else is really just very superficial.

781
00:35:55.050 --> 00:35:58.710
What is the uric acid lowering agent treatment of choice?

782
00:35:58.710 --> 00:36:02.550
Again, allopurinol, it's the cheapest.

783
00:36:02.550 --> 00:36:05.010
Most people tolerate it really well.

784
00:36:05.010 --> 00:36:07.740
There's a genetic marker if you're concerned

785
00:36:07.740 --> 00:36:10.440
and it's the place to go.

786
00:36:10.440 --> 00:36:14.280
If, however, you're not getting to the place,

787
00:36:14.280 --> 00:36:15.690
if you're not able to get

788
00:36:15.690 --> 00:36:18.300
your uric acid below six on allopurinol

789
00:36:18.300 --> 00:36:21.330
and you've increased the dose say up to 600 milligrams,

790
00:36:21.330 --> 00:36:24.600
if that's the case and they're still symptomatic,

791
00:36:24.600 --> 00:36:27.450
that will be a good time to switch to Uloric

792
00:36:27.450 --> 00:36:28.890
because there's some studies that show you

793
00:36:28.890 --> 00:36:31.920
that you can push the dose of Uloric a little bit higher

794
00:36:31.920 --> 00:36:35.730
and gain a little additional efficacy at the higher doses.

795
00:36:35.730 --> 00:36:40.730
So that will be kind of a niche for Uloric or- (indistinct)

796
00:36:42.090 --> 00:36:43.170
All right, is there a benefit

797
00:36:43.170 --> 00:36:44.580
to steroid injections for acute gout?

798
00:36:44.580 --> 00:36:49.580
Yes, so again, efficacy is the same with steroids,

799
00:36:49.614 --> 00:36:53.160
NSAIDs, colchicine, they're all the same.

800
00:36:53.160 --> 00:36:54.810
But yes, there's benefit

801
00:36:54.810 --> 00:36:58.950
with intra-articular steroid injections in the acute phase.

802
00:36:58.950 --> 00:36:59.783
<v ->And with that,</v>

803
00:36:59.783 --> 00:37:02.520
we're going to have to bring things to a close.

804
00:37:02.520 --> 00:37:04.980
I'm gonna turn it over to Dr. Dachs to get started

805
00:37:04.980 --> 00:37:07.530
with the peripheral vascular disease lecture.

806
00:37:07.530 --> 00:37:10.170
<v ->The quick, first quick questions.</v>

807
00:37:10.170 --> 00:37:12.027
What's the difference between an aortic aneurysm

808
00:37:12.027 --> 00:37:13.990
and an ectasia?

809
00:37:13.990 --> 00:37:17.550
So an ectasia is a dilation of an artery,

810
00:37:17.550 --> 00:37:18.930
let's say the aorta,

811
00:37:18.930 --> 00:37:21.870
but it's not greater than 50% of the,

812
00:37:21.870 --> 00:37:23.340
the diameter of the lumen.

813
00:37:23.340 --> 00:37:25.290
So it's a little bit of a dilation.

814
00:37:25.290 --> 00:37:27.240
It's not a true aneurysm yet.

815
00:37:27.240 --> 00:37:29.610
Actually, the radiologists are encouraged not to use

816
00:37:29.610 --> 00:37:30.720
that term anymore

817
00:37:30.720 --> 00:37:33.420
'cause it just confuses the heck out of everybody.

818
00:37:33.420 --> 00:37:37.020
What's the difference between an eccentric

819
00:37:37.020 --> 00:37:39.420
and saccular type of aneurysm?

820
00:37:39.420 --> 00:37:40.860
They're the same thing.

821
00:37:40.860 --> 00:37:45.860
It's just one wall of the vessel comes out.

822
00:37:46.069 --> 00:37:50.430
Not a fusiform, the whole thing circumferentially dilating.

823
00:37:50.430 --> 00:37:51.538
Those are the difference between the two.

824
00:37:51.538 --> 00:37:54.330
ABI, is it done sitting, standing or lying down?

825
00:37:54.330 --> 00:37:57.690
You typically glide the patient down to get to their legs.

826
00:37:57.690 --> 00:37:58.830
Definition of ever smoked?

827
00:37:58.830 --> 00:38:00.663
It's 100 cigarettes in a lifetime.

828
00:38:03.480 --> 00:38:05.340
If you have an ABI greater than 1.4,

829
00:38:05.340 --> 00:38:07.290
do you send the patient for duplex sonography?

830
00:38:07.290 --> 00:38:09.660
Yeah, you start working them up, yes.

831
00:38:09.660 --> 00:38:12.003
How long do you prescribe cilostazol for?

832
00:38:12.894 --> 00:38:15.933
If it's working, kind of indefinitely.

833
00:38:16.920 --> 00:38:19.650
Unless then they go for some surgery and corrective stuff

834
00:38:19.650 --> 00:38:21.333
and then you get the stop, right?

835
00:38:23.250 --> 00:38:25.650
I think that's where I'll stop there

836
00:38:25.650 --> 00:38:27.090
and I'll go over to my colleague-

837
00:38:27.090 --> 00:38:28.140
<v ->Dr. Gilmer.</v>
<v ->Shall, I answer</v>

838
00:38:28.140 --> 00:38:30.030
the rest of these online.

839
00:38:30.030 --> 00:38:31.740
<v ->You guys had some great questions,</v>

840
00:38:31.740 --> 00:38:34.713
probably more questions than any other group we've had.

841
00:38:35.940 --> 00:38:37.860
I answered all of them online.

842
00:38:37.860 --> 00:38:39.030
There are a couple,

843
00:38:39.030 --> 00:38:43.080
there were many questions on subclinical hypothyroidism.

844
00:38:43.080 --> 00:38:45.720
So when you are subclinically hypothyroid,

845
00:38:45.720 --> 00:38:48.900
that means you technically don't have symptoms.

846
00:38:48.900 --> 00:38:51.090
So if you don't have symptoms

847
00:38:51.090 --> 00:38:54.570
and your TSH is floating higher, say nine,

848
00:38:54.570 --> 00:38:56.250
you don't have to treat that.

849
00:38:56.250 --> 00:38:57.960
So there's that.

850
00:38:57.960 --> 00:38:59.490
If they become symptomatic

851
00:38:59.490 --> 00:39:01.140
and they have a TSH of nine,

852
00:39:01.140 --> 00:39:02.990
then clearly, you need to treat that.

853
00:39:04.350 --> 00:39:07.260
If a patient is in a higher risk state,

854
00:39:07.260 --> 00:39:12.260
i.e, cardiovascular disease, osteoporosis, et cetera,

855
00:39:12.450 --> 00:39:14.700
you can consider getting a TPO antibody

856
00:39:14.700 --> 00:39:18.120
because a TPO antibody just further risk stratifies

857
00:39:18.120 --> 00:39:22.230
if they might progress towards fulminant hypothyroidism.

858
00:39:22.230 --> 00:39:24.600
So that's the nuance there.

859
00:39:24.600 --> 00:39:26.490
<v ->In a way you shouldn't even know about those people.</v>

860
00:39:26.490 --> 00:39:29.100
You shouldn't be screening for hypothyroidism

861
00:39:29.100 --> 00:39:30.990
unless there's overt disease.

862
00:39:30.990 --> 00:39:32.010
I recently had a patient

863
00:39:32.010 --> 00:39:33.960
who said I cannot tolerate levothyroxine.

864
00:39:33.960 --> 00:39:35.370
She was on this low dose.

865
00:39:35.370 --> 00:39:36.570
I'm like, "Why are you on it?"

866
00:39:36.570 --> 00:39:38.910
They said, well, they said, "I had hypothyroidism."

867
00:39:38.910 --> 00:39:41.970
TSH was 13, completely asymptomatic.

868
00:39:41.970 --> 00:39:44.610
I did a search, she's got a 20% chance

869
00:39:44.610 --> 00:39:47.040
of developing hypothyroidism.

870
00:39:47.040 --> 00:39:49.410
But there was no indication to treat her at this point,

871
00:39:49.410 --> 00:39:50.937
even with the TSH of 13.

872
00:39:50.937 --> 00:39:53.520
And most of these patients come in, you can find them,

873
00:39:53.520 --> 00:39:55.467
they're on 25 micrograms of levothyroxine

874
00:39:55.467 --> 00:39:58.440
and you're like, "How did they diagnose you?"

875
00:39:58.440 --> 00:39:59.760
Dr. Gilmer, continue.

876
00:39:59.760 --> 00:40:02.700
<v ->You can always just consider surveillance too,</v>

877
00:40:02.700 --> 00:40:04.980
two, three months as we, as in that previous patient.

878
00:40:04.980 --> 00:40:07.500
Much questions about thyroid nodule, like what do you do?

879
00:40:07.500 --> 00:40:09.270
What is the surveillance pattern

880
00:40:09.270 --> 00:40:11.190
after you identify a nodule,

881
00:40:11.190 --> 00:40:13.593
it's a nodule that that doesn't look concerning,

882
00:40:14.430 --> 00:40:16.260
it's less than one centimeter.

883
00:40:16.260 --> 00:40:20.430
The Academy of Clinical Endocrinology has a whole list

884
00:40:20.430 --> 00:40:22.830
of criteria that will help guide you

885
00:40:22.830 --> 00:40:26.550
as to what you need to do, the morphology of the lesion,

886
00:40:26.550 --> 00:40:28.593
the size of the lesion, et cetera.

887
00:40:30.780 --> 00:40:33.300
Otherwise, all of your other discreet questions

888
00:40:33.300 --> 00:40:35.190
I answered online.

889
00:40:35.190 --> 00:40:36.510
<v ->Dr. Dachs.</v>

890
00:40:36.510 --> 00:40:38.340
<v ->So someone asked about</v>

891
00:40:38.340 --> 00:40:40.920
the ischemic stroke question number five.

892
00:40:40.920 --> 00:40:43.380
Is the answer not aspirin

893
00:40:43.380 --> 00:40:46.923
since I put in the dosages 325 versus 81?

894
00:40:48.240 --> 00:40:49.950
When they come in the ER, we give them,

895
00:40:49.950 --> 00:40:51.510
we typically have them chew

896
00:40:51.510 --> 00:40:53.940
four 81 milligram tablets, so 324.

897
00:40:53.940 --> 00:40:55.530
We give them a full dose aspirin

898
00:40:55.530 --> 00:40:57.090
for an acute ischemic stroke.

899
00:40:57.090 --> 00:40:59.340
And that's what people usually started on

900
00:40:59.340 --> 00:41:02.220
with their acute ischemic strokes, not 81 milligrams.

901
00:41:02.220 --> 00:41:06.300
What's the role of Plavix clopidogrel

902
00:41:06.300 --> 00:41:08.700
in acute stroke?

903
00:41:08.700 --> 00:41:10.200
I hope I cleared this up.

904
00:41:10.200 --> 00:41:15.200
If it's an NIHSS score greater than three,

905
00:41:16.050 --> 00:41:20.880
I'm not giving Plavix for acute stroke.

906
00:41:20.880 --> 00:41:25.880
If it's a TIA or an NIHS score less than three,

907
00:41:26.370 --> 00:41:28.620
then I will use clopidogrel

908
00:41:28.620 --> 00:41:31.830
as part of my dual anti-platelets, okay?

909
00:41:31.830 --> 00:41:32.663
That clear?

910
00:41:32.663 --> 00:41:34.200
I hope that's clear now.

911
00:41:34.200 --> 00:41:36.270
I love this one, do Good Samaritan laws vary

912
00:41:36.270 --> 00:41:39.823
if the plane is an international flight? (laughs)

913
00:41:41.280 --> 00:41:42.330
Generally not.

914
00:41:42.330 --> 00:41:44.790
But I will tell you there's actually, Australia,

915
00:41:44.790 --> 00:41:46.372
I know Australia and I think there's a couple of others

916
00:41:46.372 --> 00:41:51.372
if you're on Qantas for example, you have a duty to assist

917
00:41:52.770 --> 00:41:55.530
and you can get in trouble if they find out you're a doctor

918
00:41:55.530 --> 00:41:57.600
and you didn't assist.

919
00:41:57.600 --> 00:42:01.050
Okay, they have, you must assist in certain countries,

920
00:42:01.050 --> 00:42:03.210
but Qantas I know is one of them.

921
00:42:03.210 --> 00:42:04.140
It's kind of interesting.

922
00:42:04.140 --> 00:42:08.370
<v ->My very first assist was leaving a board review course</v>

923
00:42:08.370 --> 00:42:10.380
and I had to assist twice on the plane

924
00:42:10.380 --> 00:42:12.360
with two different people.

925
00:42:12.360 --> 00:42:13.950
<v ->Oh really?</v>
<v ->I've never done that before.</v>

926
00:42:13.950 --> 00:42:15.540
<v ->Yeah</v>
<v ->Craziness.</v>

927
00:42:15.540 --> 00:42:17.343
<v ->Well, you know, for those of you who've done this,</v>

928
00:42:17.343 --> 00:42:18.176
I mean-

929
00:42:18.176 --> 00:42:20.259
<v ->I got a $500 voucher on a flight to Singapore</v>

930
00:42:20.259 --> 00:42:21.183
for assisting with-
<v ->Yeah, definitely.</v>

931
00:42:21.183 --> 00:42:22.830
<v ->I've done three times.</v>

932
00:42:22.830 --> 00:42:26.820
Once I got a voucher, once I got nothing,

933
00:42:26.820 --> 00:42:27.900
twice I got nothing.

934
00:42:27.900 --> 00:42:29.310
You get nothing.

935
00:42:29.310 --> 00:42:31.710
And doing it, it's really tough.

936
00:42:31.710 --> 00:42:34.320
There is like no space, you have to find a spot.

937
00:42:34.320 --> 00:42:35.910
Like you have to take the patient

938
00:42:35.910 --> 00:42:40.290
and move them into, you know, an area

939
00:42:40.290 --> 00:42:43.500
if you're doing resuscitation or CPR, it's not easy.

940
00:42:43.500 --> 00:42:44.820
I will tell you one other funniest story

941
00:42:44.820 --> 00:42:45.870
if I can, just about this.

942
00:42:45.870 --> 00:42:47.940
So my wife is an ICU nurse

943
00:42:47.940 --> 00:42:50.160
and one of the things they called the doctor for,

944
00:42:50.160 --> 00:42:51.300
there's a woman right across from us

945
00:42:51.300 --> 00:42:52.410
who was having a panic attack.

946
00:42:52.410 --> 00:42:53.940
It was just, she was just, it was,

947
00:42:53.940 --> 00:42:55.950
she was all over the place, it was terrible, you know.

948
00:42:55.950 --> 00:42:59.970
And so my wife has much more empathy than I do.

949
00:42:59.970 --> 00:43:00.960
<v ->You're kidding me.</v>

950
00:43:00.960 --> 00:43:05.340
<v ->But yeah, (laughs) sat there, talked her the whole flight,</v>

951
00:43:05.340 --> 00:43:06.390
the whole flight.

952
00:43:06.390 --> 00:43:09.030
So we, you know, I assessed the woman, of course,

953
00:43:09.030 --> 00:43:10.470
my wife did the whole thing.

954
00:43:10.470 --> 00:43:14.970
We get off the plane, my wife is PO'd to this day.

955
00:43:14.970 --> 00:43:16.927
Everybody came up to me and said, "Great job, doc."

956
00:43:16.927 --> 00:43:18.060
"Great job, doc."

957
00:43:18.060 --> 00:43:20.910
And didn't say anything to my wife. (laughs)

958
00:43:20.910 --> 00:43:22.680
So true story.

959
00:43:22.680 --> 00:43:23.700
All right, enough of that.

960
00:43:23.700 --> 00:43:25.050
Do I have time for one or two more, David?

961
00:43:25.050 --> 00:43:25.883
I don't know where I'm at time-

962
00:43:25.883 --> 00:43:27.120
<v ->You have time for one more.</v>

963
00:43:27.120 --> 00:43:29.100
<v ->Okay. (chuckles)</v>

964
00:43:29.100 --> 00:43:31.230
Does considering anticoagulation change

965
00:43:31.230 --> 00:43:34.350
if you have paroxysmal AFib versus persistent AFib?

966
00:43:34.350 --> 00:43:35.580
That's a great question.

967
00:43:35.580 --> 00:43:36.600
Most of the cardiologists

968
00:43:36.600 --> 00:43:39.570
and most everybody says even for paroxysmal AFib,

969
00:43:39.570 --> 00:43:43.050
you should consider putting them on anticoagulation.

970
00:43:43.050 --> 00:43:45.750
Yes, that's the answer on that one, yeah.

971
00:43:45.750 --> 00:43:48.090
David, can I just make one addendum to one answer

972
00:43:48.090 --> 00:43:49.950
I guess just gave here about the Plavix in acute stroke?

973
00:43:49.950 --> 00:43:51.360
<v ->Yes.</v>
<v ->Take two seconds, I'm sorry.</v>

974
00:43:51.360 --> 00:43:54.420
I said we don't use Plavix in acute stroke

975
00:43:54.420 --> 00:43:57.630
with an NIHS score greater than three, the big strokes.

976
00:43:57.630 --> 00:44:00.180
One caveat or exception to that rule is

977
00:44:00.180 --> 00:44:03.180
if the patient has an aspirin allergy,

978
00:44:03.180 --> 00:44:06.060
then you would use the clopidogrel.

979
00:44:06.060 --> 00:44:07.710
There's a nuance.

980
00:44:07.710 --> 00:44:09.990
<v ->Thank you very much, we'll be back at 10 o'clock.</v>

981
00:44:09.990 --> 00:44:12.690
<v ->Okay, lots of questions here.</v>

982
00:44:12.690 --> 00:44:15.690
Probably four times as many as we normally get

983
00:44:15.690 --> 00:44:16.980
for one of these talks.

984
00:44:16.980 --> 00:44:19.653
So you guys have been paying attention.

985
00:44:20.550 --> 00:44:24.840
There are a lot of questions in the CKD lecture about,

986
00:44:24.840 --> 00:44:29.840
again, the use of ACEs and ARBs and when do you do that?

987
00:44:31.380 --> 00:44:36.380
Patients who have diabetes and hypertension,

988
00:44:37.620 --> 00:44:42.300
patients who have diabetes and CKD,

989
00:44:42.300 --> 00:44:44.280
those are individuals who would benefit

990
00:44:44.280 --> 00:44:45.903
from an ACE or an ARB.

991
00:44:47.250 --> 00:44:51.270
Patients who have chronic kidney disease

992
00:44:51.270 --> 00:44:53.970
not related to diabetes.

993
00:44:53.970 --> 00:44:58.970
Those individuals will also benefit from a certain ARB,

994
00:45:00.900 --> 00:45:05.640
especially, if they have the presence of albuminuria

995
00:45:05.640 --> 00:45:07.923
or that they are hypertensive.

996
00:45:08.790 --> 00:45:11.370
Patients who have diabetes,

997
00:45:11.370 --> 00:45:14.280
but do not have hypertension,

998
00:45:14.280 --> 00:45:17.280
do not have CKD,

999
00:45:17.280 --> 00:45:20.130
do not have albumin in their urine,

1000
00:45:20.130 --> 00:45:25.130
do not need to be on ACEs or ARBs to prevent kidney disease

1001
00:45:25.440 --> 00:45:27.723
in the future, okay?

1002
00:45:28.650 --> 00:45:31.143
And you may or may not see that on the board.

1003
00:45:32.250 --> 00:45:36.603
How about the workup for CKD when do you start doing that?

1004
00:45:37.560 --> 00:45:40.920
Generally, when a patient hits CKD three

1005
00:45:40.920 --> 00:45:44.010
on the basis of their GFR,

1006
00:45:44.010 --> 00:45:47.010
those folks should have a reasonable workup

1007
00:45:47.010 --> 00:45:50.820
both in terms of labs and probably an imaging study

1008
00:45:50.820 --> 00:45:53.433
to look at their kidneys, probably an ultrasound,

1009
00:45:54.420 --> 00:45:57.540
but patients with CKD one or two,

1010
00:45:57.540 --> 00:46:00.300
who have that diagnosis on the basis

1011
00:46:00.300 --> 00:46:03.210
of having polycystic kidney disease

1012
00:46:03.210 --> 00:46:07.830
on the basis of having persistent albuminuria,

1013
00:46:07.830 --> 00:46:10.290
even if they have a decent GFR,

1014
00:46:10.290 --> 00:46:13.890
you know, those folks still probably should get a workup

1015
00:46:13.890 --> 00:46:16.743
at the time that you identified that abnormality,

1016
00:46:17.580 --> 00:46:18.720
<v Dr. Weismiller>Dr. Dachs.</v>

1017
00:46:18.720 --> 00:46:21.570
<v ->And so this goes back to the first lecture.</v>

1018
00:46:21.570 --> 00:46:23.400
How are we supposed to measure compartments?

1019
00:46:23.400 --> 00:46:24.233
Are we supposed to measure

1020
00:46:24.233 --> 00:46:25.500
compartment syndromes in the office?

1021
00:46:25.500 --> 00:46:27.660
I don't know of any office setting that has this set up

1022
00:46:27.660 --> 00:46:29.880
to do a compartment syndrome measurement.

1023
00:46:29.880 --> 00:46:31.737
We do it in the ER, it is a very simple thing.

1024
00:46:31.737 --> 00:46:33.600
You just put a needle in.

1025
00:46:33.600 --> 00:46:35.130
We used to hook it up to manometer,

1026
00:46:35.130 --> 00:46:37.082
but now there's this electronic little piece

1027
00:46:37.082 --> 00:46:39.330
to do it in there and gives you the pressure.

1028
00:46:39.330 --> 00:46:41.880
Are you diagnosing retinal hemorrhages in young children

1029
00:46:41.880 --> 00:46:44.008
on CT or ophthalmoscope?

1030
00:46:44.008 --> 00:46:44.958
(coughs) Excuse me.

1031
00:46:46.050 --> 00:46:48.540
So retinal hemorrhages, you got to do an ophthalmoscope,

1032
00:46:48.540 --> 00:46:49.950
that's the way you do it

1033
00:46:49.950 --> 00:46:53.850
if you have intracerebral hemorrhages you'll find it on CT.

1034
00:46:53.850 --> 00:46:56.790
What's, and this one's I don't have the right answer for.

1035
00:46:56.790 --> 00:47:01.533
Where is the line for a dirty wound versus clean?

1036
00:47:02.490 --> 00:47:03.330
There's no line.

1037
00:47:03.330 --> 00:47:05.940
I mean, it's dirty versus clean.

1038
00:47:05.940 --> 00:47:07.823
I mean, what do you think is dirty clean?

1039
00:47:09.240 --> 00:47:11.520
Is there no lifting restriction needed

1040
00:47:11.520 --> 00:47:12.570
for patients with hernia?

1041
00:47:12.570 --> 00:47:13.740
No, there's not, I know,

1042
00:47:13.740 --> 00:47:16.470
I know we've been telling patients for years, don't lift.

1043
00:47:16.470 --> 00:47:18.300
If you've got a hernia, you'll make it worse.

1044
00:47:18.300 --> 00:47:20.190
You know, they can lift, they can, you know,

1045
00:47:20.190 --> 00:47:22.980
would I tell them to be go, you know,

1046
00:47:22.980 --> 00:47:25.650
be a professional weightlifter

1047
00:47:25.650 --> 00:47:27.960
and start, you know, bench pressing 300 pounds?

1048
00:47:27.960 --> 00:47:29.190
No, no I wouldn't do that,

1049
00:47:29.190 --> 00:47:33.213
but a simple exercise and mild lifting is just fine.

1050
00:47:34.050 --> 00:47:34.950
Excuse me.

1051
00:47:34.950 --> 00:47:37.080
Why no Betadine to clean the wound again?

1052
00:47:37.080 --> 00:47:39.030
There's a couple of people ask that.

1053
00:47:39.030 --> 00:47:42.210
Betadine into the wound is cytotoxic.

1054
00:47:42.210 --> 00:47:45.390
If you dilute out the Betadine like 100 to one,

1055
00:47:45.390 --> 00:47:47.190
you can put it in, that's all right.

1056
00:47:47.190 --> 00:47:50.730
Betadine on the intact skin around the wound is fine,

1057
00:47:50.730 --> 00:47:53.010
but pouring it into the wound is what I'm referring to

1058
00:47:53.010 --> 00:47:54.903
is not where you wanna go with that.

1059
00:47:56.730 --> 00:47:58.110
How do you know it's a descending cholangitis

1060
00:47:58.110 --> 00:47:59.280
versus just cholecystitis?

1061
00:47:59.280 --> 00:48:00.960
Again, Charcot's triad.

1062
00:48:00.960 --> 00:48:04.350
If they've got, you know, if they're jaundiced,

1063
00:48:04.350 --> 00:48:06.056
and they're, you know,

1064
00:48:06.056 --> 00:48:08.253
then you know what you're dealing with.

1065
00:48:11.430 --> 00:48:15.840
And I think I've sort of answered that for the most part.

1066
00:48:15.840 --> 00:48:17.790
Yeah, that's, I'll move on to my next one.

1067
00:48:17.790 --> 00:48:19.020
<v ->Dr. Levine.</v>

1068
00:48:19.020 --> 00:48:21.660
<v ->Yeah, there's a question about metformin</v>

1069
00:48:21.660 --> 00:48:24.720
and checking a creatinine GFR.

1070
00:48:24.720 --> 00:48:26.520
When do you do that?

1071
00:48:26.520 --> 00:48:28.230
You should know the patient's creatinine

1072
00:48:28.230 --> 00:48:31.080
in order to safely treat them with metformin.

1073
00:48:31.080 --> 00:48:35.040
So if you don't have one recently before you start,

1074
00:48:35.040 --> 00:48:36.930
then go ahead and get one, you know,

1075
00:48:36.930 --> 00:48:38.310
within a short period of time

1076
00:48:38.310 --> 00:48:41.463
to make sure it's safe to continue on their therapy.

1077
00:48:42.360 --> 00:48:47.360
Question about hydration in relation to contrast studies.

1078
00:48:48.660 --> 00:48:50.700
How much do you use?

1079
00:48:50.700 --> 00:48:54.300
There's no specific regimen or protocol for that.

1080
00:48:54.300 --> 00:48:57.240
Most of the studies that have looked at it have indicated

1081
00:48:57.240 --> 00:48:58.230
that it's safe,

1082
00:48:58.230 --> 00:49:01.200
doesn't cause people to go into pulmonary edema.

1083
00:49:01.200 --> 00:49:04.500
And usually, they're using doses about a milliliter

1084
00:49:04.500 --> 00:49:06.900
per kilogram per hour.

1085
00:49:06.900 --> 00:49:10.200
So 75 to a 100 mls per hour.

1086
00:49:10.200 --> 00:49:12.844
Maybe start a couple hours before the procedure,

1087
00:49:12.844 --> 00:49:16.890
continue for, you know, a couple hours or more afterwards.

1088
00:49:16.890 --> 00:49:19.560
If you have a hospitalized patient, it's easy to do that.

1089
00:49:19.560 --> 00:49:22.050
In outpatient, you're probably not gonna hydrate them

1090
00:49:22.050 --> 00:49:23.190
for as long

1091
00:49:23.190 --> 00:49:26.940
and whatever isotonic solution you like will work.

1092
00:49:26.940 --> 00:49:29.850
Question about what to do in the setting of AKI

1093
00:49:29.850 --> 00:49:31.080
with volume overload.

1094
00:49:31.080 --> 00:49:34.170
Do you treat the volume overload first with diuretics

1095
00:49:34.170 --> 00:49:35.220
or you treat the AKI?

1096
00:49:36.300 --> 00:49:38.070
Well, you treat the volume overload,

1097
00:49:38.070 --> 00:49:40.110
especially if it's pulmonary edema

1098
00:49:40.110 --> 00:49:43.800
because if you do that you may improve their cardiac output

1099
00:49:43.800 --> 00:49:47.790
to renal perfusion and the AKI may get a whole lot better.

1100
00:49:47.790 --> 00:49:48.960
But while you're doing that,

1101
00:49:48.960 --> 00:49:52.440
you're also looking for other reasons for the AKI

1102
00:49:52.440 --> 00:49:53.910
and you're treating those

1103
00:49:53.910 --> 00:49:56.010
so to help the patient get better quicker.

1104
00:49:58.680 --> 00:50:02.250
Do you have to memorize normal ranges of values

1105
00:50:02.250 --> 00:50:05.670
related to protein excretion for the boards?

1106
00:50:05.670 --> 00:50:07.230
Yeah, I would know what difference

1107
00:50:07.230 --> 00:50:11.580
between normal microalbuminuria and macroalbuminuria.

1108
00:50:11.580 --> 00:50:13.440
I think that's fair game for you.

1109
00:50:13.440 --> 00:50:15.273
The others probably not as much.

1110
00:50:16.170 --> 00:50:17.188
<v ->Dr. Dachs.</v>

1111
00:50:17.188 --> 00:50:18.021
<v ->Okay.</v>

1112
00:50:19.200 --> 00:50:22.980
Do we see similar MRSA proliferation outside

1113
00:50:22.980 --> 00:50:24.630
of the United States?

1114
00:50:24.630 --> 00:50:27.420
I don't know the answer to that question.

1115
00:50:27.420 --> 00:50:29.470
I can look it up but I really don't know.

1116
00:50:31.410 --> 00:50:35.430
This is actually a good question and the next one.

1117
00:50:35.430 --> 00:50:37.140
Up where I am now in my neck of the woods,

1118
00:50:37.140 --> 00:50:39.030
when you see a seven nerve cranial palsy

1119
00:50:39.030 --> 00:50:43.140
and are not sure if it's Lyme or Bell's palsy,

1120
00:50:43.140 --> 00:50:46.710
how do you treat them while you wait for my results?

1121
00:50:46.710 --> 00:50:48.150
You're absolutely right.

1122
00:50:48.150 --> 00:50:51.240
It is a real quandary

1123
00:50:51.240 --> 00:50:55.593
and we do our best to try to get some sort of sense.

1124
00:50:56.460 --> 00:50:58.260
Is this person at risk for Lyme disease?

1125
00:50:58.260 --> 00:50:59.670
Are they outside a lot?

1126
00:50:59.670 --> 00:51:03.340
Are they, you know, it becomes, it's a clinical call

1127
00:51:04.560 --> 00:51:06.810
and as you know, if you think it's a Bell's,

1128
00:51:06.810 --> 00:51:09.030
then you should start them on steroids.

1129
00:51:09.030 --> 00:51:11.850
When it comes to Lyme, there's been actually some suggestion

1130
00:51:11.850 --> 00:51:13.560
that you shouldn't start the steroids

1131
00:51:13.560 --> 00:51:15.480
and so it leaves us in a real quandary

1132
00:51:15.480 --> 00:51:19.110
and you just do your best clinical judgment

1133
00:51:19.110 --> 00:51:21.360
on whether you think this person is,

1134
00:51:21.360 --> 00:51:23.190
falls on one side of the equation or the other.

1135
00:51:23.190 --> 00:51:25.263
It's not a good situation to be in.

1136
00:51:27.180 --> 00:51:28.530
Let's do the next one.

1137
00:51:28.530 --> 00:51:31.530
Does Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction only occur with penicillin

1138
00:51:31.530 --> 00:51:33.120
or does it occur with doxycyline?

1139
00:51:33.120 --> 00:51:35.760
Any antibiotic that's gonna kill those spirochetes.

1140
00:51:35.760 --> 00:51:37.530
Again, they're exploding, they're dying,

1141
00:51:37.530 --> 00:51:39.450
and you're not, it's gonna happen.

1142
00:51:39.450 --> 00:51:42.150
I did not know this, maybe some can look this up for me.

1143
00:51:42.150 --> 00:51:44.190
According to UpToDate,

1144
00:51:44.190 --> 00:51:46.770
amoxicillin should be edited to doxycycline

1145
00:51:46.770 --> 00:51:48.900
for MRSA cellulitis.

1146
00:51:48.900 --> 00:51:50.370
Do you agree with this?

1147
00:51:50.370 --> 00:51:52.290
And since I'm not aware of that yet.

1148
00:51:52.290 --> 00:51:55.650
I haven't seen that recommendation, I'm not sure why.

1149
00:51:55.650 --> 00:51:58.650
<v ->Be careful with UpToDate though when you're using it,</v>

1150
00:51:58.650 --> 00:52:00.977
because there is some opinion

1151
00:52:00.977 --> 00:52:02.040
in there.
<v ->Opinion, yeah.</v>

1152
00:52:02.040 --> 00:52:05.490
<v ->That is not necessarily evidence-based.</v>

1153
00:52:05.490 --> 00:52:07.560
<v ->Yeah.</v>
<v ->So be careful</v>

1154
00:52:07.560 --> 00:52:10.230
if you're gonna, particularly on the longitudinal exam,

1155
00:52:10.230 --> 00:52:12.540
you're going to that as your resource.

1156
00:52:12.540 --> 00:52:13.530
<v Dr. Dachs>Yeah.</v>

1157
00:52:13.530 --> 00:52:15.960
<v ->There is opinion in there and you will see it.</v>

1158
00:52:15.960 --> 00:52:18.870
They'll say, "In our practice here at."

1159
00:52:18.870 --> 00:52:20.280
<v ->Right.</v>
<v ->"We do this."</v>

1160
00:52:20.280 --> 00:52:21.270
<v ->Right.</v>
<v ->Okay, so be careful</v>

1161
00:52:21.270 --> 00:52:22.650
with that, okay?
<v ->Right.</v>

1162
00:52:22.650 --> 00:52:24.270
Yeah, and that was the example I gave

1163
00:52:24.270 --> 00:52:26.910
with the cat scratch.

1164
00:52:26.910 --> 00:52:29.280
Yeah, they said, yeah, give antibiotics

1165
00:52:29.280 --> 00:52:32.280
where you look at other textbooks and they say no,

1166
00:52:32.280 --> 00:52:34.020
you don't do it.

1167
00:52:34.020 --> 00:52:34.853
At one or two more here,

1168
00:52:34.853 --> 00:52:36.750
it is really, this is a good question.

1169
00:52:36.750 --> 00:52:38.610
What is the recommended duration of antibiotics

1170
00:52:38.610 --> 00:52:40.020
for MRSA cellulitis?

1171
00:52:40.020 --> 00:52:42.120
7 days or 14 days?

1172
00:52:42.120 --> 00:52:43.830
Everybody in general,

1173
00:52:43.830 --> 00:52:46.590
shorten the courses of your antibiotics please.

1174
00:52:46.590 --> 00:52:50.190
No more 14 days for cellulitis.

1175
00:52:50.190 --> 00:52:53.250
Five to seven is fine, okay.

1176
00:52:53.250 --> 00:52:54.120
It is good.

1177
00:52:54.120 --> 00:52:55.560
<v ->I'm gonna post a paper</v>

1178
00:52:55.560 --> 00:52:57.840
from the American Board of Internal Medicine.

1179
00:52:57.840 --> 00:52:59.640
We did a presentation on this last year,

1180
00:52:59.640 --> 00:53:02.940
Family Medicine Update, looking at outpatient treatment,

1181
00:53:02.940 --> 00:53:04.620
five days of antibiotics,

1182
00:53:04.620 --> 00:53:06.660
which is really where things are moving.

1183
00:53:06.660 --> 00:53:10.757
So I'm gonna post that to one of the Q&amp;As

1184
00:53:10.757 --> 00:53:12.030
before you guys leave.

1185
00:53:12.030 --> 00:53:13.560
<v ->Okay.</v>
<v ->Okay.</v>

1186
00:53:13.560 --> 00:53:15.330
I'm gonna ask Bob to take one last one

1187
00:53:15.330 --> 00:53:17.550
and then Gary to take two and then we've got to do our call

1188
00:53:17.550 --> 00:53:19.500
because we're running low on time here.

1189
00:53:20.850 --> 00:53:24.060
<v ->Someone wrote, what about TXA,</v>

1190
00:53:24.060 --> 00:53:26.280
tranexamic acid for angioedema?

1191
00:53:26.280 --> 00:53:27.480
It usually works in about 20 minutes.

1192
00:53:27.480 --> 00:53:30.180
There's been plus minus on that that's out there

1193
00:53:30.180 --> 00:53:31.980
as well as FFP is the other thing

1194
00:53:31.980 --> 00:53:35.430
people have talked about using angioedema.

1195
00:53:35.430 --> 00:53:39.240
And I'm talking about ACE-induced angioedema here,

1196
00:53:39.240 --> 00:53:41.970
plus minus the data is weak if anything, okay.

1197
00:53:41.970 --> 00:53:43.020
<v Dr. Weismiller>Dr. Levine.</v>

1198
00:53:43.020 --> 00:53:46.260
<v ->Is proteinuria same thing as albuminuria?</v>

1199
00:53:46.260 --> 00:53:47.610
No, it's not.

1200
00:53:47.610 --> 00:53:51.450
Albuminuria is the most common type of proteinuria,

1201
00:53:51.450 --> 00:53:54.030
but you can get proteinuria,

1202
00:53:54.030 --> 00:53:57.240
Bence-Jones proteinuria for example for myelomas.

1203
00:53:57.240 --> 00:53:59.610
That's not gonna show up on a dipstick.

1204
00:53:59.610 --> 00:54:02.490
And maybe very important for your patient.

1205
00:54:02.490 --> 00:54:06.420
What about a patient who has increased creatinine on a PPI?

1206
00:54:06.420 --> 00:54:07.800
What should you do?

1207
00:54:07.800 --> 00:54:11.670
Should you stop the PPI and recheck the BMP?

1208
00:54:11.670 --> 00:54:13.020
And the answer to that is yeah,

1209
00:54:13.020 --> 00:54:15.390
if you suspect that's the problem

1210
00:54:15.390 --> 00:54:16.680
because the creatinine bumped

1211
00:54:16.680 --> 00:54:20.070
after you started the PPI then stop it

1212
00:54:20.070 --> 00:54:23.280
and recheck your creatinine in a week to two weeks later.

1213
00:54:23.280 --> 00:54:26.370
But you might also look at the urine for eosinophils

1214
00:54:26.370 --> 00:54:28.170
and if it's positive then you know exactly

1215
00:54:28.170 --> 00:54:31.020
that that's the reason and then you can, you know,

1216
00:54:31.020 --> 00:54:33.170
then treat the patient normally after that.

1217
00:54:34.050 --> 00:54:36.330
<v ->Please join me in thanking our colleagues,</v>

1218
00:54:36.330 --> 00:54:37.163
particularly, Dr. Dachs.

1219
00:54:37.163 --> 00:54:39.313
You will be taking leave from us.

1220
00:54:39.313 --> 00:54:40.264
(audience applauding)
<v ->Thank you.</v>

1221
00:54:40.264 --> 00:54:42.090
<v ->I'm gonna ask Dr. Levine to go ahead and get started.</v>

1222
00:54:42.090 --> 00:54:45.570
I have answered almost all of mine online

1223
00:54:45.570 --> 00:54:50.570
so please refer to that for your answers for my questions.

1224
00:54:50.580 --> 00:54:51.660
I have a couple more to do

1225
00:54:51.660 --> 00:54:53.880
but I will finish those up and Gary,

1226
00:54:53.880 --> 00:54:55.230
take it away please, sir.

1227
00:54:55.230 --> 00:54:58.200
<v ->Yeah, there are a couple questions as always come up.</v>

1228
00:54:58.200 --> 00:55:01.020
What do you do if you have a patient on opioids,

1229
00:55:01.020 --> 00:55:03.180
you have a contract with them

1230
00:55:03.180 --> 00:55:06.063
and they test positive for marijuana THC?

1231
00:55:07.080 --> 00:55:09.600
The problem, the reason that you do

1232
00:55:09.600 --> 00:55:11.610
the urine drug testing is two reasons.

1233
00:55:11.610 --> 00:55:14.970
One is to find out if they're taking the medication

1234
00:55:14.970 --> 00:55:17.250
that you have them on

1235
00:55:17.250 --> 00:55:18.083
and the other,

1236
00:55:18.083 --> 00:55:20.640
are they taking something that they shouldn't?

1237
00:55:20.640 --> 00:55:23.520
Specifically things that could either interact

1238
00:55:23.520 --> 00:55:26.220
with the medicines that you're using

1239
00:55:26.220 --> 00:55:28.874
or suggest that they really have a preference

1240
00:55:28.874 --> 00:55:30.780
for some other drug

1241
00:55:30.780 --> 00:55:32.940
and they're gonna use your prescription

1242
00:55:32.940 --> 00:55:35.430
to sell on the street to finance the thing

1243
00:55:35.430 --> 00:55:36.603
that they really want.

1244
00:55:37.650 --> 00:55:40.890
You know, marijuana, when it was illegal,

1245
00:55:40.890 --> 00:55:45.000
it had more of a connotation of abuse

1246
00:55:45.000 --> 00:55:46.740
and you would worry

1247
00:55:46.740 --> 00:55:50.430
that your patient is gonna sell your oxycodone

1248
00:55:50.430 --> 00:55:52.203
and then buy their marijuana.

1249
00:55:53.190 --> 00:55:56.310
So what you do with a patient individually is look at

1250
00:55:56.310 --> 00:55:58.290
that individual risk

1251
00:55:58.290 --> 00:55:59.654
and if you're concerned

1252
00:55:59.654 --> 00:56:02.490
that you know, the marijuana use is gonna interfere

1253
00:56:02.490 --> 00:56:03.840
with what you're using,

1254
00:56:03.840 --> 00:56:05.940
you fear that they really are selling your drug

1255
00:56:05.940 --> 00:56:07.350
to buy marijuana,

1256
00:56:07.350 --> 00:56:09.810
then whether it's legal or it's illegal,

1257
00:56:09.810 --> 00:56:12.720
then you might not wanna continue the contract.

1258
00:56:12.720 --> 00:56:14.490
And if you're worried about that upfront,

1259
00:56:14.490 --> 00:56:17.340
you put that in the contract before you start,

1260
00:56:17.340 --> 00:56:18.270
say "Listen, you know,

1261
00:56:18.270 --> 00:56:20.790
you know I'm worried about you smoking marijuana

1262
00:56:20.790 --> 00:56:24.000
five times a day and it's not gonna work my opioid.

1263
00:56:24.000 --> 00:56:25.800
And if you do that and it shows up,

1264
00:56:25.800 --> 00:56:29.190
then we're gonna have to do this a little bit differently.

1265
00:56:29.190 --> 00:56:31.530
So I think you look at the individual patient,

1266
00:56:31.530 --> 00:56:34.230
you decide what the risk is and you can use that

1267
00:56:34.230 --> 00:56:36.930
to determine whether the contract stays in place

1268
00:56:36.930 --> 00:56:39.273
or is eliminated and how you work from there.

1269
00:56:40.710 --> 00:56:43.200
There is also a question about things

1270
00:56:43.200 --> 00:56:47.700
that may give you a false positive urine drug test.

1271
00:56:47.700 --> 00:56:49.830
The thing that really strikes you

1272
00:56:49.830 --> 00:56:53.370
or comes out is the patients who have colds and coughs

1273
00:56:53.370 --> 00:56:56.130
and they go to the drugstore and they get pseudoephedrine

1274
00:56:56.130 --> 00:56:57.420
and then they test positive

1275
00:56:57.420 --> 00:57:00.330
for methamphetamines in the urine.

1276
00:57:00.330 --> 00:57:02.490
And that's a fairly common thing

1277
00:57:02.490 --> 00:57:04.770
because some folks were using pseudoephedrine

1278
00:57:04.770 --> 00:57:07.950
and similar things to that at home to make methamphetamines,

1279
00:57:07.950 --> 00:57:10.020
it's pretty closely related

1280
00:57:10.020 --> 00:57:11.430
and at least in North Carolina,

1281
00:57:11.430 --> 00:57:13.620
if you go to get pseudoephedrine,

1282
00:57:13.620 --> 00:57:16.410
the pharmacist will take your picture and of your license

1283
00:57:16.410 --> 00:57:20.040
and tell you if you come back too often you get this again,

1284
00:57:20.040 --> 00:57:21.780
they're gonna report to the authorities

1285
00:57:21.780 --> 00:57:24.570
'cause it really was a big issue for us.

1286
00:57:24.570 --> 00:57:26.973
So that's the one that most commonly comes up.

1287
00:57:27.810 --> 00:57:28.743
